[2] Turkey (Tokat)
A.
Date: Tue 19 Apr 2022 14:24 TRT
Source: News Bouquet, Ä°hlas News Agency report [in Turkish, machine trans., edited]
https://haberbuketi.net/2022/04/19/olumcul-kene-vakalari-gorulmeye-baslandi/


In Tokat, where the Crimean-Congo hemorrhagic fever (CCHF) was first seen in Turkey, cases started to be seen again with the arrival of spring.

Tokat State Hospital Infectious Diseases and Clinical Microbiology Specialist Bahadir Orkun Ozbay stated that tick complaints started in the spring. Reminding that the 1st case in Turkey was seen in Tokat in 2002, Ozbay warned the citizens to be more careful in the spring period. Ozbay, who advised the citizens who will go to the picnic, especially those who deal with livestock and farmers, to be careful against ticks, listed the measures to be taken.

Ozbay said, "We need to wear light-colored and closed clothes in vineyards, gardens, forests, and rural areas. This tick is not transmitted by jumping, it is transmitted by climbing up the human body and then clinging to it. We need to lay a light-colored cloth on the ground so that we can spot the tick at the picnic. After leaving the countryside, we need to check ourselves when we return home. In particular, we need to check places such as the bottom of our hair, our neck, and armpits," he said.

Ozbay underlined that the tick should not be touched with bare hands and said, "If we see a tick clinging to our body, we definitely do not touch it with bare hands. We can remove it with a plastic glove or nylon. Or the most important thing is to consult a health center as soon as possible for the prompt removal of the tick. The 2nd most important point is that chemicals should not be spilled on it, cigarettes should not be extinguished at work, and should not be crushed by hand. If the person can remove the tick it should be removed appropriately or quickly apply to the health institution.

Stating that Crimean-Congo hemorrhagic fever is a viral disease like COVID-19, Ozbay said, "The tick is the carrier here. A virus in the tick causes the disease. It can be transmitted by ticks clinging to bare skin. Apart from that, it can be transmitted by breaking or crushing the ticks we see on the animal with bare hands."

Infected animals and people can transmit the virus via their blood, tissues, and secretions. This is one of the important points. Some of our CCHF patients do not have a history of tick contact. Therefore, those living in endemic areas need to know what symptoms they may develop.

Since these are viral diseases, general symptoms such as weakness, nausea, vomiting, fever, muscle pain, and diarrhea can be seen. Of course, there is no such thing as CCHF disease when these symptoms are seen. But a blood test can be done in this respect by applying to the hospital," he said.

--
