----
B.
Date: Thu 21 Apr 2022 10:40
Source: Ä°hlas News Agency [in Turkish, machine trans., edited]
https://www.haberler.com/saglik/sicakliklarin-artmasiyla-birlikte-kene-vakalari-14886016-haberi/


With the increase in temperatures, tick cases started to be seen. Citizens were warned that the Crimean-Congo hemorrhagic fever [CCHF], which may occur as a result of tick bites, will seriously threaten human health, and that the tick population will increase with the warming of the weather.

Crimean-Congo hemorrhagic fever was first recognized in Turkey in 2002-2003. CCHF still exists in Tokat and Kelkit Valley. The disease affects many people every year, especially in Central Anatolia and the adjacent provinces of the Eastern Black Sea Region, especially in the Kelkit Valley area. While the disease is common in the center of Erzincan and in the rural areas of its districts, the 1st case of the year [2022] was seen in Tokat again.

Assoc Dr Faruk Karakestated that with the warming of the weather, the number of cases will increase in the coming period, as it was last year [2021], and said, "As you know, as we enter the hot summer months, we expect to see cases in the spring. Frankly, Crimean-Congo hemorrhagic fever is a disease we see in our region every year. Normally, we have been seeing around 30-40 cases in the last 10 years, until the [COVID-19] pandemic period in 2019. However, we have detected a significant increase in this number in the last 2 years, around 100 cases. We saw the cases and the cases were a bit more severe. Another important point is that when we interviewed the surrounding provinces where the cases were intense, such as Erzurum and Sivas, there was a similar situation there. Of course, there were many reasons for this. Social reasons came first. With the COVID-19 pandemic, the increase in restrictions, curfews, etc. Then we realized that the tendency of people to go to rural areas increased. Again, in the fight against this tick, it was a little secondary when dealing with the fight against the pandemic, such as spraying, etc., in rural areas. We know there is a little more.

This year [2022], we have passed mid-April and the year has been very rainy and a little cold. We have not seen a definite case in our province yet, but as the weather warms up, the cases will probably start to come and it will continue until October-November. We see the largest case density as of May and peaks in June-July, as it does every year. In this respect, I would like to especially warn our citizens in rural areas. The disease progresses with similar findings to those of COVID-19 -- fever, muscle pain, weakness, etc. It can come with symptoms such as bleeding and can cause serious disease and death. In this respect, our citizens in rural areas need to be alert to diseases, and when their complaints begin, they should immediately go to health institutions, so that we can provide the necessary support and care with early intervention and treatment.

"What can be done to prevent ticks?"
Assoc Dr Faruk Karake also warned the citizens about the precautions they can take and said, "What can be done for those who go to the countryside or go for a picnic? As we all know, we say that ticks are on the ground. They do not fly and they do not fall on us from trees, etc. For example, one of the simplest and most effective methods is to tuck the trousers into the socks. Very simple precautions can be taken, such as, wearing light-colored clothes, wearing closed shoes instead of sandals, and spraying insect repellent on trousers or feet if going to the countryside. "If there is, we need to find it," he said.

[Byline: Emin Ferhat Sevilir]

