[3] Iraq
Date: Mon 9 May 2022
Source: Almada [in Arabic, machine trans., edited]
https://almadapaper.net/view.php?cat=264351


The Ministry of Health reported that the spread of the [Crimean-Congo] hemorrhagic fever virus is still limited, but it warned against ignoring the preventive measures, stressing that most of the infections and deaths occurred in Dhi Qar Governorate. Ministry spokesman, Saif Al-Badr said, "the epidemiological situation of (the Crimean-Congo) hemorrhagic fever so far is the registration of 40 cases, 8 of which have died, 20 have recovered, and 16 others are still receiving medical care in health institutions."

Al-Badr continued "the most infections (cases) were in Dhi Qar, which accounted for the largest number of deaths, with 5 cases." He pointed out "the other cases were distributed by a case (the 2nd) in Babil, Al- Muthanna governorate, and the 3rd in Kirkuk," stressing that "there are other cases suspected of being infected, subject to isolation procedures until confirmed." Al-Badr indicated that "all health institutions in Iraq can diagnose cases and provide medical services, especially in their early stages," reiterating that "there is no vaccine or direct treatment for the virus until the present time." He also stated, "the procedures for protecting animals and combating the tick that transmits the virus, are the responsibility of the Ministry of Agriculture," noting that "random slaughter and transportation of animals fall on the shoulders of the municipal authorities and the Baghdad Municipality, and there are measures taken by the Ministry of Interior in this regard," Al-Badr explained.

He stated that "the symptoms of the disease are high temperature, pain in different areas of the body, fatigue, headaches, and stomach aches, and this is the 1st stage in which the symptoms are relatively simple, but once detected, the recovery rates will be very high after providing supportive treatment." Al-Badr warned against "reaching the 2nd stage, which is the most dangerous of bleeding under the skin in the form of bruises or bleeding from the openings (orifices), and here the complications will be more severe and may end in death."

Al-Badr added, "the most vulnerable groups to infection are livestock breeders of all kinds, such as sheep, cows, goats, horses, and those who work in transporting livestock or butchers." He also stressed that "the risk will be greater if the patient has immune disorders, and an important point that must be emphasized (is) that the infected person can transmit the infection to another, and this constitutes a challenge for us, in addition to the possibility of transmission through contact with the infected animal or through the vector (tick).

Al-Badr concluded, "The cases are still limited and followed up by us, and we hope not to raise fears without justification, but at the same time we warn against indifference to this virus, and therefore we should deal with reality professionally and scientifically because they are sensitive issues." For his part, Deputy Speaker of Parliament Shakhwan Abdullah warned of the danger of the repercussions of the outbreak of the hemorrhagic fever virus and the high number of infections and deaths. Abdullah, according to an official statement received by Al-Mada, demanded the "Federal Government accelerate the formation of a joint committee by the Ministry of Health that is supported by all relevant entities and security institutions to contain the infection and the health impact of the virus" and calling for the isolation of the affected areas.

Abdullah emphasized "the need to prevent contact, apply precautionary measures, take urgent health measures by the Ministry of Health, and allocate hospitals and health centers to treat the infected and provide the medicines and medical supplies they need."

The Ministry of Health had confirmed in previous statements that Iraq has recorded limited cases of [Crimean-Congo] hemorrhagic fever annually since the [1970s], but these numbers have increased during the current year [2022].

--
Communicated by:
ProMED Rapporteur Mahmoud Orabi

[The current outbreak in Dhi Qar has so far registered 28 cases, of which 5 have died. Other affected Iraqi governorates, include Nineveh, Kirkuk, Najaf, Muthanna, Maysan, and Basra.

ProMED map of Iraq: https://promedmail.org/promed-post?place=8702957,89

Crimean-Congo hemorrhagic fever (CCHF) is a widespread disease caused by a tick-borne virus (_Nairovirus_) of the Bunyaviridae family. The CCHF virus causes severe viral hemorrhagic fever outbreaks, with a case fatality rate of 10-40%.

Animals become infected by the bite of infected ticks and the virus remains in their bloodstream for about one week after infection, allowing the tick-animal-tick cycle to continue when another tick bites. Although several tick genera are capable of becoming infected with the CCHF virus, ticks of the genus _Hyalomma_ are the principal vector.

It is important to raise awareness about the risk factors of the disease, particularly in the population groups likely to be exposed to the virus, and educate them to take precautionary measures to reduce exposure to the virus, such as wearing gloves and protective clothing while handling animals.

Furthermore, appropriate capacity building and training of public health rapid response teams (RRT) should be carried out to equip them to control any future outbreaks of this anthropo-zoonotic disease. - Mod.UBA]
